"Yes, Captain. By now you should be on your way, they were still in the mess hall picking up their meals."   Exactly at 0500, the Exodus Company gathered by the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"Shaw explained, 'We are being moved to the forward base I-131, fifty miles outside of Ianlos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and the later attack on Ianlos in order to drive out the rebels. There, we will establish a base at the foot of the mountains,' he said. 'March to your troops and mount up.'"
The company dissolved into the respective squads, and the soldiers were distributed by the corporals onto the tanks. Cohren climbed onto one of the tanks further ahead in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered the arrival of the two a few days earlier but knew little about them. He sat on the side, letting his legs dangle, while he adjusted his backpack and the radio equipment connected to his headset and throat microphone.
"Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?" Nemic asked after they had settled in.
"Do you mean the rooster he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning when they let the animal roam on a farm. "Yes, I think so."
Cohren looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. From the corner of his eye, he noticed the movement of a small hen that was constantly turning its head to scan the surroundings.
"Yes, he is still with him," answered Cohren, as the hatch of the tank opened and the commander came into view.
"All tanks, advance," said the commander slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the tank train and Strykers roared to life as they began moving. The Kronos tank, on which Cohren was riding, shook as the brakes were released and they joined the formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania plain. Despite the winter storms, the swampy areas had frozen and the woods were covered in snow, yet the mud was everywhere.
After about an hour, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, began to speak. "Lieutenant, have you been here since the start of the war, right?"
"Yes, Operation Firestorm," Cohren answered. "We thought the matter would be settled in a few weeks, but we underestimated it."
"Underestimated is greatly underestimated," Nemic interjected into the conversation. "We were not prepared for their arsenal and the number of soldiers. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and only last month the Erebus. We should have even seen them on our way."
" I stand firmly by the side of the Federation," said Orson defiantly. "I won't let these terrorists intimidate me."
"You're saying that now. But I've seen that most eighteen-year-old recruits, like you, take cover immediately the moment they hear a shot," explained Craith.
"We'll see about that," Cohren said, laughing. Orson ended the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We're picking up heat signatures, about 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right."
Cohren climbed up on the tank and put on his special goggles. When he switched them to "thermal imaging," he could spot the signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I see her," Cohren replied over his throat microphone.
"Are they hostile?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"I can't see that," answered Cohren. He reached for his microphone and said, "Exodus squad, fire only when under fire. Let's lure them out."
As they approached, the point-like heat signatures took shape. As they drew even closer, one of them hurried off to fetch something. Immediately, she returned to the small elevation where the others were. The figures lay down on the ground, assuming shooting positions.
"Contact with the enemy," Shaw called over the radio as orange tracer rounds were fired from the hilltop. While the tanks came under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket streaked past and hit behind the formation, striking the ground and exploding, scattering debris and rubble over one of the tanks. Another struck sideways into a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly climbed out and took cover as the ammunition exploded into the air.
" Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 meters. Fire at will," shouted the tank commander over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, shells flew toward the hill and exploded, sending mud and rock into the air.
"Send the Sentis in," Knoxx called out, observing the high ground through a pair of binoculars. The rear hatch of a Cerberus opened, and an unarmed soldier emerged, wearing a special headset. He called out orders into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially called Sentinels, stormed out. Swinging their thin, metallic arms and legs forward, they burst into a sprint. They carried their weapons on their backs.
"Kill or capture?" asked Craith as they watched.
"Captivity seems likely," Cohren speculated as the two sentinels vanished into the ash and smoke cloud. Shouts and gunshots echoed from the hilltop, but quickly faded away. A short time later, the two sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them whose boots left tracks in the ground. After returning to the safety of the train, they threw the figure to the ground. She groaned in pain as she landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw went to the figure that was just trying to stand up. Then he turned to one of the sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, Sir," answered the sentinel. "The rest fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing nearby. "Get that guy out of my sight!"
